          "id": "f1",
          "severity": "blocking",
          "description": "The canonical package artifacts are named as basenames or slug templates in the draft, while the required outputs for this role are full tool-relative paths. That mismatch is already reflected by the self-check errors and means the package is not structurally freeze-ready.",
          "source_section": "<outputs>; Contract summary.package_files; Self-check issues"
        },
        {
          "id": "f2",
          "severity": "major",
          "description": "The guardrail \"All role artifacts must be slug-prefixed\" is contradicted by declared artifacts such as result.json, normalized-request.json, source-manifest.json, self-check.json, resume-package.json, and runtime/session-registry.json. The package currently defines an invariant it cannot satisfy.",
          "source_section": "<guardrails>; <steps>; <outputs>"
        },
        {
          "id": "f3",
          "severity": "major",
          "description": "Completion requires all applicable artifacts to be written to the output directory, but the same draft also says frozen artifacts are promoted to canonical package locations. That leaves the terminal artifact model ambiguous between run-scoped evidence and canonical promoted files.",
          "source_section": "<completion>; <steps>; <outputs>"
        }
      ],
      "redesign_guidance": "Choose one explicit artifact model and apply it everywhere. Declare canonical outputs as full tool-relative paths under tools/agent-role-builder/role/, declare run-scoped evidence as full paths under tools/agent-role-builder/runs/<job-id>/, narrow or remove the blanket slug-prefix rule so generic evidence files are legal, and make <completion> explicitly distinguish run completion from canonical promotion."
    },
    {
      "id": "group-2",
      "summary": "The board-review loop is not authority-safe: it allows stale approvals and underconstrained arbitration semantics inside a process that claims strict governed freeze rules.",
      "severity": "blocking",
      "findings": [
        {
          "id": "f4",
          "severity": "blocking",
          "description": "Step 4 says to iterate only with the rejecting reviewer, but the guardrails say freeze only when every reviewer approves. Once the draft changes, prior approvals are stale unless the approving reviewers re-review the revised artifact; that requirement is not stated.",
          "source_section": "<steps>; <guardrails>"
        },
        {
          "id": "f5",
          "severity": "major",
          "description": "Arbitration is introduced as a general response after consecutive split verdicts, but the draft does not bound arbitration to minor-only disputes or forbid it from resolving blocking/major pushback. That expands governance semantics beyond what is clearly authorized.",
          "source_section": "<steps>; Contract summary.governance"
        },
        {
          "id": "f6",
          "severity": "major",
          "description": "The package claims subordination to the architecture source but its review lifecycle has no explicit place for the required rule-learning/update control between review and fix, so the governed loop it defines is incomplete relative to its own stated authority chain.",
          "source_section": "<authority>; <steps>"
        }
      ],
      "redesign_guidance": "Redefine the review loop so any material draft revision invalidates earlier approvals unless explicitly re-confirmed, constrain arbitration to the exact allowed boundary, and add the missing governance control points required by the parent review architecture rather than inventing a lighter-weight local variant."
    }
  ],
  "residual_risks": [
    "Even after the markdown is fixed, the contract generator and validator may still emit basename-based paths unless their implementation is aligned and re-run.",
    "The self-role/bootstrap case remains high-coupling; any exception added for agent-role-builder itself could silently weaken the general role-governance model."
  ],
  "strengths": [
    "The required top-level tagged structure is present and broadly coherent.",
    "The scope section makes a useful attempt to separate role-package governance from tool creation and broader runtime orchestration.",
    "The guardrails correctly emphasize no invented semantics and no freeze while material pushback remains."
  ]
}

